# Performance Optimization: Rendering, Caching, and Memory Management

*Unlock blazing-fast UI performance in OpenMaui applications with advanced techniques for render caching, dirty region management, GPU acceleration, and native resource lifecycle control.*

## Introduction

Performance optimization in modern UI frameworks is a multifaceted challenge that requires understanding the entire rendering pipeline—from how pixels are drawn to the screen to how native resources are managed in memory. OpenMaui's Linux implementation, built on SkiaSharp and native windowing systems, provides a rich set of optimization opportunities that can dramatically improve application responsiveness and reduce resource consumption.

This article dives deep into the performance optimization techniques available in OpenMaui applications running on Linux. We'll explore how the `SkiaRenderingEngine` manages dirty regions to minimize redraws, how render caching can eliminate redundant drawing operations, and when to choose GPU acceleration over software rendering. We'll also examine critical memory management patterns for P/Invoke interop and advanced rendering strategies for complex UIs.

Whether you're building a lightweight utility or a complex enterprise application, these techniques will help you achieve smooth 60 FPS performance while keeping memory usage under control. The strategies discussed here are based on real implementation patterns from the OpenMaui codebase, which successfully runs full .NET MAUI applications on Linux with 100% API compliance.

## Performance Profiling Tools

Before optimizing anything, you need accurate measurements. OpenMaui applications benefit from multiple profiling approaches that reveal different aspects of performance bottlenecks.

## Built-in Frame Timing

The `SkiaRenderingEngine` includes frame timing diagnostics that can be enabled during development:

```csharp
public class PerformanceMonitor
{
    private readonly Stopwatch _frameTimer = new();
    private readonly Queue<double> _frameTimes = new(60);

    public void OnFrameStart()
    {
        _frameTimer.Restart();
    }

    public void OnFrameEnd()
    {
        var elapsed = _frameTimer.Elapsed.TotalMilliseconds;
        _frameTimes.Enqueue(elapsed);

        if (_frameTimes.Count > 60)
            _frameTimes.Dequeue();

        var avgFrameTime = _frameTimes.Average();
        var fps = 1000.0 / avgFrameTime;

        Debug.WriteLine($"Frame: {elapsed:F2}ms | Avg FPS: {fps:F1}");
    }
}
```

## Skia Performance Flags

SkiaSharp provides performance tracking through `SKPaint` and `SKCanvas` profiling. Enable these during development:

```csharp
public void MeasureDrawOperation(SKCanvas canvas, Action<SKCanvas> drawAction)
{
    var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();
    drawAction(canvas);
    sw.Stop();

    if (sw.ElapsedMilliseconds > 16) // Exceeds 60 FPS budget
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"⚠️ Slow draw operation: {sw.ElapsedMilliseconds}ms");
    }
}
```

## Native Memory Profiling

For P/Invoke-heavy code, use `dotnet-counters` to monitor native allocations:

```bash
# Monitor GC and native allocations
dotnet-counters monitor --process-id <PID> \
  System.Runtime[gen-0-gc-count,gen-1-gc-count,gen-2-gc-count] \
  System.Runtime[alloc-rate,gc-heap-size]
```

## X11/GTK Event Loop Profiling

The `LinuxDispatcher` uses GLib's main loop. Profile event processing overhead:

```csharp
public class DispatcherProfiler
{
    public void ProfileEventProcessing()
    {
        var before = GC.GetTotalMemory(false);
        var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();

        // Process pending events
        while (gtk_events_pending())
        {
            gtk_main_iteration();
        }

        sw.Stop();
        var after = GC.GetTotalMemory(false);
        var allocated = after - before;

        Console.WriteLine($"Event loop: {sw.ElapsedMilliseconds}ms, " +
                         $"Allocated: {allocated / 1024}KB");
    }
}
```

## Identifying Bottlenecks

Common performance bottlenecks in OpenMaui applications:

1. **Excessive redraws**: Check if dirty region management is working correctly
2. **Font shaping overhead**: HarfBuzz text shaping can be expensive for complex scripts
3. **Image decoding**: Large images decoded on the UI thread
4. **Collection rendering**: `SkiaCollectionView` with non-virtualized items
5. **P/Invoke marshaling**: Frequent string conversions between managed and native code

Use these profiling tools to establish baselines before applying optimizations, then measure again to validate improvements.

## Render Cache and TextRenderCache

Caching rendered content is one of the most effective optimization techniques available. OpenMaui's Skia-based rendering system provides multiple caching strategies to eliminate redundant drawing operations.

## Understanding Render Caching

Every time a view is drawn, SkiaSharp executes a series of drawing commands—filling rectangles, stroking paths, rendering text with font shaping. For static or infrequently changing content, this work is wasteful. Render caching stores the output of these operations in an `SKBitmap` or `SKImage` that can be quickly blitted to the canvas.

## Implementing View-Level Caching

The `SkiaView` base class supports render caching through a simple pattern:

```csharp
public class CachedSkiaView : SkiaView
{
    private SKBitmap? _renderCache;
    private bool _cacheInvalidated = true;

    protected override void OnPropertyChanged(string propertyName = null)
    {
        base.OnPropertyChanged(propertyName);

        // Invalidate cache when visual properties change
        if (propertyName == nameof(BackgroundColor) ||
            propertyName == nameof(Width) ||
            propertyName == nameof(Height))
        {
            InvalidateCache();
        }
    }

    public void InvalidateCache()
    {
        _cacheInvalidated = true;
        InvalidateSurface();
    }

    protected override void OnDraw(SKCanvas canvas, int width, int height)
    {
        if (_cacheInvalidated || _renderCache == null)
        {
            // Recreate cache
            _renderCache?.Dispose();
            _renderCache = new SKBitmap(width, height);

            using var cacheCanvas = new SKCanvas(_renderCache);
            DrawContent(cacheCanvas, width, height);

            _cacheInvalidated = false;
        }

        // Fast blit from cache
        canvas.DrawBitmap(_renderCache, 0, 0);
    }

    protected virtual void DrawContent(SKCanvas canvas, int width, int height)
    {
        // Expensive drawing operations here
    }

    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
    {
        if (disposing)
        {
            _renderCache?.Dispose();
        }
        base.Dispose(disposing);
    }
}
```

## Text Render Caching

Text rendering with HarfBuzz shaping is particularly expensive for complex scripts (Arabic, Devanagari, CJK). The `SkiaLabel` implementation benefits significantly from text caching:

```csharp
public class TextRenderCache
{
    private readonly Dictionary<TextCacheKey, SKTextBlob> _cache = new();
    private const int MaxCacheSize = 1000;

    private record TextCacheKey(
        string Text,
        string FontFamily,
        float FontSize,
        SKFontStyleWeight Weight,
        SKFontStyleSlant Slant
    );

    public SKTextBlob GetOrCreateTextBlob(
        string text,
        SKFont font,
        SKPaint paint)
    {
        var key = new TextCacheKey(
            text,
            font.Typeface.FamilyName,
            font.Size,
            font.Typeface.FontWeight,
            font.Typeface.FontSlant
        );

        if (_cache.TryGetValue(key, out var cached))
        {
            return cached;
        }

        // Perform expensive text shaping
        var blob = SKTextBlob.Create(text, font);

        // Evict old entries if cache is full
        if (_cache.Count >= MaxCacheSize)
        {
            var oldest = _cache.Keys.First();
            _cache[oldest].Dispose();
            _cache.Remove(oldest);
        }

        _cache[key] = blob;
        return blob;
    }

    public void Clear()
    {
        foreach (var blob in _cache.Values)
        {
            blob.Dispose();
        }
        _cache.Clear();
    }
}
```

Integrate this into `SkiaLabel`:

```csharp
public class OptimizedSkiaLabel : SkiaLabel
{
    private static readonly TextRenderCache _textCache = new();

    protected override void DrawText(SKCanvas canvas, SKPaint paint)
    {
        using var font = paint.ToFont();
        var textBlob = _textCache.GetOrCreateTextBlob(Text, font, paint);

        canvas.DrawText(textBlob, (float)X, (float)Y, paint);
    }
}
```

## Image Caching Strategy

The `SkiaImage` control implements multi-level caching:

```csharp
public class ImageCacheManager
{
    private readonly MemoryCache _memoryCache;
    private readonly string _diskCacheDir;

    public ImageCacheManager()
    {
        _memoryCache = new MemoryCache(new MemoryCacheOptions
        {
            SizeLimit = 100 * 1024 * 1024 // 100 MB
        });

        _diskCacheDir = Path.Combine(
            Environment.GetFolderPath(Environment.SpecialFolder.LocalApplicationData),
            "OpenMaui", "ImageCache"
        );
        Directory.CreateDirectory(_diskCacheDir);
    }

    public async Task<SKBitmap?> GetOrLoadImageAsync(
        string source,
        CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        var cacheKey = ComputeHash(source);

        // Level 1: Memory cache
        if (_memoryCache.TryGetValue<SKBitmap>(cacheKey, out var cached))
        {
            return cached;
        }

        // Level 2: Disk cache
        var diskPath = Path.Combine(_diskCacheDir, cacheKey + ".skia");
        if (File.Exists(diskPath))
        {
            var bitmap = SKBitmap.Decode(diskPath);
            CacheInMemory(cacheKey, bitmap);
            return bitmap;
        }

        // Level 3: Load from source
        var loaded = await LoadImageAsync(source, ct);
        if (loaded != null)
        {
            await SaveToDiskAsync(diskPath, loaded);
            CacheInMemory(cacheKey, loaded);
        }

        return loaded;
    }

    private void CacheInMemory(string key, SKBitmap bitmap)
    {
        var size = bitmap.ByteCount;
        _memoryCache.Set(key, bitmap, new MemoryCacheEntryOptions
        {
            Size = size,
            SlidingExpiration = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)
        });
    }
}
```

## When to Use Caching

**Cache aggressively:**
- Static labels and icons
- Complex vector graphics (SVG)
- Formatted text with multiple styles
- Background gradients and patterns

**Cache selectively:**
- List item templates in `SkiaCollectionView`
- Navigation bar backgrounds
- Custom control chrome (borders, shadows)

**Don't cache:**
- Animated content
- Real-time data visualizations
- User input controls (Entry, Editor)
- Content that changes every frame

Proper caching can reduce CPU usage by 50-70% in typical business applications with mostly static content.

## DirtyRectManager Optimization

The `DirtyRectManager` is the cornerstone of efficient rendering in OpenMaui. Instead of redrawing the entire window on every frame, dirty region tracking identifies the minimal set of rectangles that need repainting.

## How Dirty Region Tracking Works

When a view's visual properties change (color, size, position), it marks its bounding rectangle as "dirty." The rendering engine accumulates these dirty regions and, during the next frame, only redraws the affected areas.

```csharp
public class DirtyRectManager
{
    private readonly List<SKRect> _dirtyRegions = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();

    public void MarkDirty(SKRect rect)
    {
        lock (_lock)
        {
            _dirtyRegions.Add(rect);
        }
    }

    public void MarkDirty(double x, double y, double width, double height)
    {
        MarkDirty(new SKRect(
            (float)x,
            (float)y,
            (float)(x + width),
            (float)(y + height)
        ));
    }

    public SKRect[] GetDirtyRegions()
    {
        lock (_lock)
        {
            if (_dirtyRegions.Count == 0)
                return Array.Empty<SKRect>();

            // Optimize: merge overlapping rectangles
            var optimized = OptimizeDirtyRegions(_dirtyRegions);
            _dirtyRegions.Clear();

            return optimized;
        }
    }

    private SKRect[] OptimizeDirtyRegions(List<SKRect> regions)
    {
        if (regions.Count <= 1)
            return regions.ToArray();

        var merged = new List<SKRect>();
        var sorted = regions.OrderBy(r => r.Left).ThenBy(r => r.Top).ToList();

        var current = sorted[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < sorted.Count; i++)
        {
            var next = sorted[i];

            // Check if rectangles overlap or are adjacent
            if (current.IntersectsWith(next) || AreAdjacent(current, next))
            {
                // Merge rectangles
                current = SKRect.Union(current, next);
            }
            else
            {
                merged.Add(current);
                current = next;
            }
        }

        merged.Add(current);
        return merged.ToArray();
    }

    private bool AreAdjacent(SKRect a, SKRect b)
    {
        const float threshold = 10f; // Pixels

        return Math.Abs(a.Right - b.Left) < threshold ||
               Math.Abs(b.Right - a.Left) < threshold ||
               Math.Abs(a.Bottom - b.Top) < threshold ||
               Math.Abs(b.Bottom - a.Top) < threshold;
    }

    public bool ShouldRenderFullFrame(SKRect[] dirtyRegions, SKSize windowSize)
    {
        if (dirtyRegions.Length == 0)
            return false;

        var totalDirtyArea = dirtyRegions.Sum(r => r.Width * r.Height);
        var windowArea = windowSize.Width * windowSize.Height;

        // If dirty area exceeds 60% of window, just redraw everything
        return (totalDirtyArea / windowArea) > 0.6f;
    }
}
```

## Integrating with SkiaRenderingEngine

The rendering engine uses dirty regions to clip drawing operations:

```csharp
public class SkiaRenderingEngine
{
    private readonly DirtyRectManager _dirtyRectManager = new();

    public void Render(SKCanvas canvas, SkiaView rootView)
    {
        var dirtyRegions = _dirtyRectManager.GetDirtyRegions();

        if (dirtyRegions.Length == 0)
        {
            // Nothing to render
            return;
        }

        var windowSize = new SKSize((float)rootView.Width, (float)rootView.Height);

        if (_dirtyRectManager.ShouldRenderFullFrame(dirtyRegions, windowSize))
        {
            // Full frame render
            RenderView(canvas, rootView, null);
        }
        else
        {
            // Partial render with clipping
            foreach (var dirtyRect in dirtyRegions)
            {
                canvas.Save();
                canvas.ClipRect(dirtyRect);

                RenderView(canvas, rootView, dirtyRect);

                canvas.Restore();
            }
        }
    }

    private void RenderView(SKCanvas canvas, SkiaView view, SKRect? clipRect)
    {
        if (!view.IsVisible)
            return;

        var viewBounds = new SKRect(
            (float)view.X,
            (float)view.Y,
            (float)(view.X + view.Width),
            (float)(view.Y + view.Height)
        );

        // Skip views outside dirty region
        if (clipRect.HasValue && !clipRect.Value.IntersectsWith(viewBounds))
            return;

        canvas.Save();
        canvas.Translate((float)view.X, (float)view.Y);

        view.Draw(canvas, (int)view.Width, (int)view.Height);

        // Recursively render children
        if (view is SkiaLayoutView layout)
        {
            foreach (var child in layout.Children.OfType<SkiaView>())
            {
                RenderView(canvas, child, clipRect);
            }
        }

        canvas.Restore();
    }
}
```

## View-Level Dirty Tracking

Views should mark themselves dirty when visual properties change:

```csharp
public abstract class SkiaView : IView
{
    private DirtyRectManager? _dirtyRectManager;

    public void AttachDirtyRectManager(DirtyRectManager manager)
    {
        _dirtyRectManager = manager;
    }

    protected void MarkDirty()
    {
        _dirtyRectManager?.MarkDirty(X, Y, Width, Height);
    }

    public Color BackgroundColor
    {
        get => _backgroundColor;
        set
        {
            if (_backgroundColor != value)
            {
                _backgroundColor = value;
                MarkDirty();
                OnPropertyChanged();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

## Layout Optimization

Layouts should propagate dirty regions from children:

```csharp
public class SkiaStackLayout : SkiaLayoutView
{
    protected override void OnChildPropertyChanged(SkiaView child, string propertyName)
    {
        base.OnChildPropertyChanged(child, propertyName);

        if (propertyName == nameof(child.Width) ||
            propertyName == nameof(child.Height))
        {
            // Child size changed, might affect layout
            InvalidateLayout();
            MarkDirty(); // Mark entire layout dirty
        }
        else
        {
            // Only child appearance changed
            _dirtyRectManager?.MarkDirty(
                child.X,
                child.Y,
                child.Width,
                child.Height
            );
        }
    }
}
```

## Performance Impact

Dirty region optimization provides dramatic performance improvements:

- **Small UI updates** (single button click): 80-90% reduction in rendering time
- **List scrolling**: 50-60% reduction by only rendering visible items
- **Animations**: 30-40% reduction by clipping to animated region

## Best Practices

1. **Granular invalidation**: Only mark the minimal affected area dirty
2. **Batch updates**: Accumulate property changes before invalidating
3. **Avoid full-window invalidation**: Reserve for theme changes or window resizes
4. **Profile dirty regions**: Log region counts and sizes to identify excessive invalidation
5. **Optimize merging**: Adjacent dirty regions should be merged to reduce draw calls

## GPU vs Software Rendering Trade-offs

OpenMaui supports both GPU-accelerated rendering via OpenGL and software rendering via CPU-based rasterization. Choosing the right rendering mode is critical for optimal performance across different hardware configurations.

## Understanding the Rendering Backends

### GPU Rendering with OpenGL

The `GpuRenderingEngine` uses SkiaSharp's OpenGL backend to leverage hardware acceleration:

```csharp
public class GpuRenderingEngine : IDisposable
{
    private GRContext? _grContext;
    private SKSurface? _surface;

    public bool Initialize(IntPtr glContext, int width, int height)
    {
        try
        {
            var glInterface = GRGlInterface.Create();
            if (glInterface == null)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Failed to create GL interface");
                return false;
            }

            _grContext = GRContext.CreateGl(glInterface);

            var frameBufferInfo = new GRGlFramebufferInfo(
                fboId: 0, // Default framebuffer
                format: SKColorType.Rgba8888.ToGlSizedFormat()
            );

            var backendRenderTarget = new GRBackendRenderTarget(
                width,
                height,
                sampleCount: 0,
                stencilBits: 8,
                frameBufferInfo
            );

            _surface = SKSurface.Create(
                _grContext,
                backendRenderTarget,
                GRSurfaceOrigin.BottomLeft,
                SKColorType.Rgba8888
            );

            return _surface != null;
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"GPU initialization failed: {ex.Message}");
            return false;
        }
    }

    public void Render(Action<SKCanvas> drawAction)
    {
        if (_surface == null || _grContext == null)
            return;

        var canvas = _surface.Canvas;
        canvas.Clear(SKColors.White);

        drawAction(canvas);

        canvas.Flush();
        _grContext.Flush();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _surface?.Dispose();
        _grContext?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Software Rendering

Software rendering uses CPU-based rasterization, which is more predictable but slower:

```csharp
public class SoftwareRenderingEngine : IDisposable
{
    private SKBitmap? _bitmap;
    private SKCanvas? _canvas;

    public void Initialize(int width, int height)
    {
        _bitmap = new SKBitmap(width, height, SKColorType.Rgba8888, SKAlphaType.Premul);
        _canvas = new SKCanvas(_bitmap);
    }

    public void Render(Action<SKCanvas> drawAction)
    {
        if (_canvas == null)
            return;

        _canvas.Clear(SKColors.White);
        drawAction(_canvas);
    }

    public IntPtr GetPixelData()
    {
        return _bitmap?.GetPixels() ?? IntPtr.Zero;
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _canvas?.Dispose();
        _bitmap?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Performance Characteristics

### GPU Rendering Advantages

- **Complex vector graphics**: 5-10x faster for paths, gradients, and effects
- **Large canvases**: Scales better with resolution (4K displays)
- **Animations**: Smooth 60 FPS even with many moving elements
- **Filters and effects**: Blur, shadows, and image filters are hardware-accelerated

### Software Rendering Advantages

- **Predictable performance**: No driver issues or GPU quirks
- **Lower latency**: No GPU context switching overhead
- **Better for simple UIs**: Faster for basic rectangles and text
- **Compatibility**: Works on all systems, including virtual machines

## Adaptive Rendering Strategy

Implement runtime selection based on content complexity:

```csharp
public class AdaptiveRenderingEngine
{
    private readonly GpuRenderingEngine _gpuEngine;
    private readonly SoftwareRenderingEngine _softwareEngine;
    private bool _useGpu;
    private int _complexityScore;

    public AdaptiveRenderingEngine()
    {
        _gpuEngine = new GpuRenderingEngine();
        _softwareEngine = new SoftwareRenderingEngine();
        _useGpu = TryInitializeGpu();
    }

    private bool TryInitializeGpu()
    {
        try
        {
            return _gpuEngine.Initialize(GetGLContext(), 1920, 1080);
        }
        catch
        {
            return false;
        }
    }

    public void Render(SkiaView rootView, Action<SKCanvas> drawAction)
    {
        // Analyze scene complexity
        _complexityScore = CalculateComplexity(rootView);

        // Use GPU for complex scenes, software for simple ones
        var shouldUseGpu = _useGpu && _complexityScore > 100;

        if (shouldUseGpu)
        {
            _gpuEngine.Render(drawAction);
        }
        else
        {
            _softwareEngine.Render(drawAction);
        }
    }

    private int CalculateComplexity(SkiaView view)
    {
        int score = 0;

        // Complex rendering operations increase score
        if (view is SkiaImage) score += 20;
        if (view is SkiaGraphicsView) score += 50;
        if (view.HasShadow) score += 10;
        if (view.HasGradient) score += 15;

        if (view is SkiaLayoutView layout)
        {
            foreach (var child in layout.Children.OfType<SkiaView>())
            {
                score += CalculateComplexity(child);
            }
        }

        return score;
    }
}
```

## GPU Acceleration Tuning

Optimize GPU rendering with these techniques:

```csharp
public class GpuOptimizationSettings
{
    // Enable MSAA for smoother edges (costs performance)
    public int SampleCount { get; set; } = 4;

    // Cache GPU resources between frames
    public bool EnableResourceCaching { get; set; } = true;

    // Use GPU texture atlas for images
    public bool UseTextureAtlas { get; set; } = true;

    public void ApplyToContext(GRContext context)
    {
        // Set resource cache limits
        if (EnableResourceCaching)
        {
            context.SetResourceCacheLimit(256 * 1024 * 1024); // 256 MB
        }

        // Purge unused resources periodically
        context.PurgeUnlockedResources();
    }
}
```

## Detecting GPU Capabilities

Query GPU capabilities to make informed decisions:

```csharp
public class GpuCapabilities
{
    public static GpuInfo DetectCapabilities()
    {
        var glInterface = GRGlInterface.Create();
        if (glInterface == null)
        {
            return new GpuInfo { Available = false };
        }

        using var context = GRContext.CreateGl(glInterface);

        return new GpuInfo
        {
            Available = true,
            MaxTextureSize = context.GetMaxTextureSize(),
            Vendor = GetGLString(GL_VENDOR),
            Renderer = GetGLString(GL_RENDERER),
            Version = GetGLString(GL_VERSION)
        };
    }

    [DllImport("libGL.so.1")]
    private static extern IntPtr glGetString(uint name);

    private static string GetGLString(uint name)
    {
        var ptr = glGetString(name);
        return Marshal.PtrToStringAnsi(ptr) ?? "Unknown";
    }

    private const uint GL_VENDOR = 0x1F00;
    private const uint GL_RENDERER = 0x1F01;
    private const uint GL_VERSION = 0x1F02;
}

public class GpuInfo
{
    public bool Available { get; set; }
    public int MaxTextureSize { get; set; }
    public string Vendor { get; set; } = "";
    public string Renderer { get; set; } = "";
    public string Version { get; set; } = "";

    public bool IsIntelIntegrated => 
        Vendor.Contains("Intel", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);

    public bool IsNvidia => 
        Vendor.Contains("NVIDIA", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);

    public bool IsAMD => 
        Vendor.Contains("AMD", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase) ||
        Vendor.Contains("ATI", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);
}
```

## Decision Matrix

| Scenario | Recommended Backend | Reason |
|----------|-------------------|--------|
| Simple business forms | Software | Lower overhead for basic shapes |
| Image-heavy applications | GPU | Hardware-accelerated image compositing |
| Data visualization | GPU | Complex paths and gradients |
| Text-heavy UIs | Software | Font rendering is fast on CPU |
| Animations | GPU | Smooth 60 FPS with hardware acceleration |
| Virtual machines | Software | GPU passthrough often unavailable |
| Low-end hardware | Software | Integrated GPUs may be slower |

## Fallback Strategy

Always implement graceful fallback:

```csharp
public class RenderingEngineFactory
{
    public static IRenderingEngine Create()
    {
        // Try GPU first
        var gpuEngine = new GpuRenderingEngine();
        if (gpuEngine.Initialize(GetGLContext(), 1920, 1080))
        {
            Console.WriteLine("✓ Using GPU rendering");
            return gpuEngine;
        }

        // Fallback to software
        Console.WriteLine("⚠ GPU unavailable, using software rendering");
        var softwareEngine = new SoftwareRenderingEngine();
        softwareEngine.Initialize(1920, 1080);
        return softwareEngine;
    }
}
```

The key is measuring real-world performance on your target hardware and choosing the backend that delivers the best user experience.

## Memory Management with P/Invoke

OpenMaui's Linux implementation relies heavily on P/Invoke for native interop with GTK, X11, and Wayland. Improper memory management in these scenarios leads to leaks, crashes, and degraded performance. This section covers essential patterns for safe native resource handling.

## Understanding Native Memory Lifecycle

When you call native functions, you're crossing the managed/unmanaged boundary. The .NET garbage collector doesn't track native allocations, so you must manually manage their lifecycle.

## SafeHandle Pattern for Native Resources

Use `SafeHandle` for automatic cleanup of native resources:

```csharp
public class GtkWidgetHandle : SafeHandle
{
    public GtkWidgetHandle() : base(IntPtr.Zero, true)
    {
    }

    public GtkWidgetHandle(IntPtr handle) : base(IntPtr.Zero, true)
    {
        SetHandle(handle);
    }

    public override bool IsInvalid => handle == IntPtr.Zero;

    protected override bool ReleaseHandle()
    {
        if (!IsInvalid)
        {
            // Properly unreference GTK widget
            gtk_widget_destroy(handle);
            g_object_unref(handle);
        }
        return true;
    }

    [DllImport("libgtk-3.so.0")]
    private static extern void gtk_widget_destroy(IntPtr widget);

    [DllImport("libgobject-2.0.so.0")]
    private static extern void g_object_unref(IntPtr obj);
}
```

Use it in your code:

```csharp
public class GtkButton : IDisposable
{
    private readonly GtkWidgetHandle _handle;

    public GtkButton(string label)
    {
        var labelPtr = Marshal.StringToHGlobalAnsi(label);
        try
        {
            var widget = gtk_button_new_with_label(labelPtr);
            _handle = new GtkWidgetHandle(widget);
        }
        finally
        {
            Marshal.FreeHGlobal(labelPtr);
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _handle?.Dispose();
    }

    [DllImport("libgtk-3.so.0")]
    private static extern IntPtr gtk_button_new_with_label(IntPtr label);
}
