## Advanced: Animated Layers

Implement smooth animations with layer opacity and transforms:

```csharp
public class AnimatedLayerController
{
    private readonly LayeredRenderer _renderer;
    private readonly Dictionary<string, Animation> _animations = new();

    public class Animation
    {
        public float StartOpacity { get; set; }
        public float EndOpacity { get; set; }
        public TimeSpan Duration { get; set; }
        public DateTime StartTime { get; set; }
        public Action? OnComplete { get; set; }
    }

    public AnimatedLayerController(LayeredRenderer renderer)
    {
        _renderer = renderer;
    }

    public void FadeIn(string layerName, TimeSpan duration, Action? onComplete = null)
    {
        var layer = _renderer.GetLayer(layerName);
        if (layer == null) return;

        layer.Opacity = 0;
        layer.IsVisible = true;

        _animations[layerName] = new Animation
        {
            StartOpacity = 0,
            EndOpacity = 1,
            Duration = duration,
            StartTime = DateTime.UtcNow,
            OnComplete = onComplete
        };
    }

    public void FadeOut(string layerName, TimeSpan duration, Action? onComplete = null)
    {
        var layer = _renderer.GetLayer(layerName);
        if (layer == null) return;

        _animations[layerName] = new Animation
        {
            StartOpacity = layer.Opacity,
            EndOpacity = 0,
            Duration = duration,
            StartTime = DateTime.UtcNow,
            OnComplete = () =>
            {
                layer.IsVisible = false;
                onComplete?.Invoke();
            }
        };
    }

    public void Update()
    {
        var now = DateTime.UtcNow;
        var completed = new List<string>();

        foreach (var (layerName, animation) in _animations)
        {
            var layer = _renderer.GetLayer(layerName);
            if (layer == null)
            {
                completed.Add(layerName);
                continue;
            }

            var elapsed = now - animation.StartTime;
            var progress = Math.Min(1.0, elapsed.TotalSeconds / animation.Duration.TotalSeconds);

            // Ease-out cubic
            var eased = 1 - Math.Pow(1 - progress, 3);

            layer.Opacity = (float)(animation.StartOpacity + 
                (animation.EndOpacity - animation.StartOpacity) * eased);

            if (progress >= 1.0)
            {
                animation.OnComplete?.Invoke();
                completed.Add(layerName);
            }
        }

        foreach (var layerName in completed)
        {
            _animations.Remove(layerName);
        }
    }
}
```

## Performance Benefits

Layered rendering provides substantial performance improvements:

- **Selective rendering**: Only dirty layers are redrawn (50-80% reduction in draw calls)
- **Caching**: Static layers rendered once and reused (90% reduction for backgrounds)
- **Parallelization**: Layers can be rendered on separate threads
- **Compositing effects**: Hardware-accelerated blending and opacity

## Use Cases

1. **Gaming UIs**: Separate background, game world, UI overlay, and cursor
2. **Image editors**: Background, canvas, tools, selection overlay
3. **Data dashboards**: Static chrome, updating charts, overlay alerts
4. **Video players**: Video layer, controls layer, subtitle layer

## Best Practices

1. **Minimize layer count**: Each layer has memory overhead
2. **Group related elements**: Don't create a layer for every control
3. **Invalidate granularly**: Only mark changed layers as dirty
4. **Use appropriate z-index spacing**: Leave room for insertion (0, 10, 20, 30...)
5. **Profile memory usage**: Each layer allocates width × height × 4 bytes
6. **Dispose properly**: Layers hold unmanaged bitmap resources

Layered rendering transforms complex UI scenarios from performance nightmares into smooth, efficient experiences.

